svg:







  Read A String From The User



  <section x="50%" y="120%" width="80%" height="150%" fill="#3498db" data-narration="There are several ways to read a string from the user, depending on the programming language and framework being used. Here are a few common methods:



Using input() function in Python

Using readline() function in Node.js

Using scanf() function in C


  <rect x="50%" y="290%" width="80%" height="40%" fill="#e74c3c" rx="10" data-narration="For example, in Python, we can use the input() function to read a string from the user:


    user_string = input('Please enter a string: ')
    print('You entered:', user_string)


  <rect x="50%" y="330%" width="80%" height="40%" fill="#2ecc71" rx="10" data-narration="Similarly, in Node.js, we can use the readline module to read a string from the user:


    const readline = require('readline');
    const rl = readline.createInterface({
      input: process.stdin,
      output: process.stdout,
    });
    rl.question('Please enter a string: ', (answer) => {
      console.log('You entered:', answer);
      rl.close();
    });


  <rect x="50%" y="370%" width="80%" height="40%" fill="#e66d6d" rx="10" data-narration="In C, we can use the scanf() function to read a string from the user:


    #include 
    int main() {
      char user_string[100];
      printf('Please enter a string: ');
      scanf("%99s", user_string);
      printf('You entered: %s\n', user_string);
      return 0;
    }



  Arrow markers represent connections between concepts.
